"While demand for all recovered paper grades has been strong this summer, it has been significantly stronger for OCC as suppliers attempt to keep up with e-commerce and packaging demand. Some recyclers and brokers say domestic mills are offering to pay prices way above the average national price as well as offering very high premiums to secure that material." "Although mills outside of the U.S. also need recovered paper to produce packaging materials, export demand has been a little soft compared with domestic demand in light of the high prices. Recyclers and brokers say mills in India and Southeast Asia need recovered paper, but many of them are holding out to see if the current high prices will drop, particularly as ocean freight rates also are high right now." https://www.recyclingtoday.com/article/recovered-paper-demand-outstrips-supply-august-2021/

{2018: 355329; 2017: 355797; 2016: 332126; 2015: 342218; 2014: 330223; 2013: 344712; 2012: 356739; 2011: 356749; 2010: 269041; 2009: 169692; 2008: 187060} It looks like the numbers before 2011 are unusable because they exclude China. The average is 345,291 (excluding <2011), STDEV = 11277. The trend is slightly down (-1204 per year), but the amount looks insignificant. 360K ~ a Z-score of 1.3 while 320K is a z-score of -2.24 and 340K is -0.47. My probability estimates are based solely on the z-scores.
Paper is expectable to go down because of teleworking, but paperboard should go up because of various pandemic-related deliveries. Both trends, however, are unlikely to be strong.
